\section{Definition}

The \textbf{Short-Term Exponential Moving Average (EMA)} is defined as:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{EMA}_t^S = \alpha_S P_t^{c} + (1 - \alpha_S) \mathrm{EMA}_{t-1}^S
\end{equation}

\noindent Similarly, the \textbf{Long-Term Exponential Moving Average (EMA)} is given by:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{EMA}_t^L = \alpha_L P_t^{c} + (1 - \alpha_L) \mathrm{EMA}_{t-1}^L
\end{equation}

where:

\begin{itemize}
    \item $\mathrm{EMA}_t^S$ : Short-Term Exponential Moving Average at time $t$.
    \item $\mathrm{EMA}_t^L$ : Long-Term Exponential Moving Average at time $t$.
    \item $P_t^{c}$ : Closing price of the asset at time $t$.
    \item $\alpha_S$ : Smoothing factor for the short EMA, defined as $\alpha_S = \frac{2}{N_S + 1}$, where $N_S$ is the period of the short EMA.
    \item $\alpha_L$ : Smoothing factor for the long EMA, defined as $\alpha_L = \frac{2}{N_L + 1}$, where $N_L$ is the period of the long EMA.
    \item $\mathrm{EMA}_{t-1}^S$ : Previous value of the short-term EMA.
    \item $\mathrm{EMA}_{t-1}^L$ : Previous value of the long-term EMA.
\end{itemize}

\noindent The \textbf{Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD)} is computed as:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{MACD}_t = \mathrm{EMA}_t^S - \mathrm{EMA}_t^L
\end{equation}

The MACD provides a measure of momentum by indicating the relationship between the short-term and long-term EMAs. A positive MACD suggests an uptrend, while a negative MACD indicates a downtrend.

\section{Strategy}

\begin{itemize}
	\item Go long at time $t+1$ if $MACD_t > 0$ and $MACD_{t-1} < 0$
	\item Go short at time $t+1$ if $MACD_t < 0$ and $MACD_{t-1} > 0$
\end{itemize}

